+- [x] **task_025: `code-check.py` shellchecks `devcontainer/git-hooks/` via a fixture-safe `CODE_CHECK_SCRIPTS` env seam** — the content-guard scanner + its three git hooks (hardened across task_019/022/023/024) had no standing `python3 code-check.py` coverage: every prior iteration had to shellcheck that directory by a separate direct invocation, because extending `scripts()` was blocked by a landmine noted in task_019's CHANGELOG entry — `smoke-test.py`'s `_patched_code_check()` fixture rewrote `scripts()` via a literal source-text `.replace()` of its exact body, so any edit silently no-op'd the patch and broke the JSON-count fixture tests. Fixed both problems together. `scripts()` now checks a new `CODE_CHECK_SCRIPTS` environment variable first: if set to a non-empty string, returns exactly the `os.pathsep`-separated `Path` list it names, in order, with no globbing and no `.exists()` filtering (the caller is declaring the exact target set); unset or empty falls through to the default set unchanged in shape except for one addition — a new git-hooks contribution, `sorted(p for p in devcontainer/git-hooks/ if p.is_file() and is_shell_script(p))`, a single flat shebang-gated pass (not a `*.sh` glob, since three of the four hook files are extensionless) appended after the `hooks/*.sh` block, then the whole candidate list `.exists()`-filtered as before. New module-level `is_shell_script(path) -> bool` is the sole shebang predicate: reads the first line defensively (`errors='ignore'`, any `OSError`/`UnicodeError` or empty file → `False`, never raises), and resolves the interpreter basename (unwrapping `#!/usr/bin/env [options] <interpreter>`, skipping `-`-prefixed option tokens like the `-S` in `#!/usr/bin/env -S bash -x`) against a `{sh, bash, dash, ksh, zsh, ash}` whitelist — deliberately excluding `fish` (whose basename is `fish`, not a `"sh" in …` substring false-positive) and non-shell interpreters. `import os` added. All four git-hooks files (`commit-msg`, `pre-c